{panel:title=From: STSP-4801}
I was trying to figure out what was eating my hard drive's space up and found a 60GB+ log file associated with SourceTree. I deleted the entire log folder ~/Library/Caches/com.crashlytics.data, and upon opening SourceTree again I saw that the crash data would be regenerated and would quickly add up in file size.

As a test, I simply opened SourceTree for 10 seconds. I did not click on anything in the app for this 10 seconds, just had it open and this generated a 10.2mb crashlytics log file, so I can see how my log file would add up to 60GB+ easily. I have attached the logs from this 10-second test.
{panel}

{quote}
See -------SRCTREE-2764------- … this feature request is closed although there is no feature implemented yet:
{quote}

h2. Explanation

When you click *ignore* in the contextual menu on a file in source tree you'll get the follow options:
 # Ignore exact filename
 # Ignore all files with this extension
 # Ignore everything beneath: [dropdown v]
 # Ignore custom pattern

It lacks the option
 - Ignore exact filename with path


h2. Example

The file in my version controlled folder is:
 {{app/design/adminhtml/default/default/layout/hackathon_emailpreview.xml}}

This will result in the following ignore strings:
 # {{hackathon_emailpreview.xml}}
 # {{*.xml}}
 # {{app/(design/(adminhtml/(default/(default/(layout/)))))}}
 # anything you type there

but it lacks:
 - {{app/design/adminhtml/default/default/layout/hackathon_emailpreview.xml}}

A customer reported:

{quote}
When viewing the log of a file, you can select "Follow renamed files" to continue viewing the history after it has been renamed.

Unfortunately, if I then try and select any of the commits to the file that happened before the rename, the diff does not show up to the right. It's just blank.
{quote}

If the commit tree can be represented as a linear history, SourceTree does so.

But that is not how the tree is typically represented in forums, tutorials, or the git manual. For example, see "man git-rebase". In there, a branch's history tends to be linear, but the existence of a branch head makes the history bifurcate - even if there is only one branch after that point. For example: 
{code}
A--B--C (master)
       `--D--E (feature)
{code}

... instead of what SourceTree would do:
{code}
A--B--C(master)--D--E(feature)
{code}

It would be nice if SourceTree had this kind of option for "branches break linearity".
